[normal]We are pleased to submit the following evidence in the name of the Parents Circle – Families Forum
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]The Parents Circle
[normal]-
[normal]F
[normal]amilies 
[normal]F
[normal]orum is an organization of more than 600 bereaved 
[normal]Palestinian and Israeli families who have lost an immediate family member in the conflict. The PCFF
[normal] w
[normal]orks to solve the conflict between Palestinians and Israelis through dialogue and mutual
[normal] 
[normal]understanding.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Given that the lack of trust and empathy between th
[normal]e sides allows for the cycle of violence to continue, 
[normal]t
[normal]he Forum presents a different and much-needed perspective on the reasons for the violence. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]To achieve this goal we work to imbue both sides with a sense of tolerance and reconciliation rather than hat
[normal]red and revenge, sharing with others our personal and painful stories. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Each day, through our activities and outreach
[normal],
[normal] the Families Forum reaffirms the sanctity of life and the need to safeguard human dignity and freedom.
[normal]The long term vision of the organi
[normal]zation is to create a framework for a reconciliation process to be an integral part of any future political peace negotiations. Without reconciliation, we believe there can only be a ceasefire, and not a lasting peace.
[normal]To lay the groundwork for a lasting p
[normal]eace, PCFF provides, first and foremost, the opportunity for Israelis and Palestinians to meet.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In the context of conflict, the two peoples remain alienated from one another, a separation which is fortified by feelings of fear, hatred, mistrust and dehuman
[normal]ization of the other.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Rather than allow bereavement to serve as yet another reason to hate, PCFF’s activities aim to use the personal stories of bereaved Israelis and Palestinians to prevent further bereavement on both sides, to demand a peaceful resolutio
[normal]n to the conflict from 
[normal]p
[normal]olicymakers and to educate the public towards reconciliation.
[normal]The PCFF’s work has been recognized by highly respected international figures
[normal],
[normal] including President Obama,
[normal] former Prime Minister and Quartet Envoy
[normal] 
[normal]Tony Blair, 
[normal]Archbishop D
[normal]esmond Tutu, US President Bill Clinton, US President Jimmy Carter, Daniel Barenboim and many others.
[normal] 
[normal]T
[normal]here is a British F
[normal]riends of the 
[normal]PCFF 
[normal]which is a registered charity
[normal] in the UK. I
[normal]ts patrons include Lord Rowan Williams, 
[normal]Lord Jonathan Sacks
[normal], Juliet Steve
[normal]nson, Dr Usama Hasan, 
[normal]Rabbi Jonathan Wittenberg
[normal], Dr Amineh Hoti, 
[normal]Karen Armstrong
[normal], 
[normal]Huw Irranca-Davies MP
[normal], 
[normal]Lord Janner of Braunstone QC
[normal] and 
[normal]Rabbi Lionel Blue
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is our deep conviction, borne out of our personal experiences, and confirmed by the impact of our activities, that promoting mutual understanding of the other within Israeli and Palestinian societies at the grass roots level is central to resolving the 
[normal]conflict. The most powerful way to do this, and the most challenging, is to bring Israelis and Palestinians face to face in a spirit of open dialogue, and not confrontation. Prior to the Second Intifada contact between the two societies was far greater. Th
[normal]at 
[normal]desperate period of conflict greatly deepened the
[normal] emotional and physical wedge between the two populations. 
[normal]Today we are struggling against the challenging political situation and the physical barriers
[normal] that separate us
[normal] which
[normal] shut down the space for dia
[normal]logue, reduce understanding, and reinforce hardline positions on both sides.  
[normal]In the context of the considerable sums spent by international donors with the aim of promoting peace between Israelis and Palestinians, we believe that grass roots reconciliati
[normal]on projects like ours are a critically important investment. 
[normal]We urge the UK government to give priority accordingly to grassroots reconciliation efforts
[normal] that
[normal] educate each side about the other and bring Israelis and Palestinians 
[normal]to the understanding that no
[normal]n-violence is the only solution to this never ending conflict
[normal].
[normal]Our 
[normal]organization
[normal] is
[normal] constantly searching for new and innovative ways to bridge the divides. Following are examples of our activities. We are proud of what we have achieved, but we are acutely a
[normal]ware that there is so much more to be done, and many more people we need to reach. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]4a. 
[normal]Youth Education
[normal]The personal stories of our members hold special significance for
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]the younger generation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Our
[normal] high school dialogue meetings address young Israeli and Palestinian students.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Since the 
[normal]S
[normal]econd Intifada there is a whole generation who have never met the “other side” and the dialogue meetings may be their first encounter.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] After hearing
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]the personal nar
[normal]ratives and the joint message of an Israeli and a Palestinian representative from the PCFF in their classroom, there is a
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]definite change in attitude and a willingness to explore the possibility of a dialogue as an alternative to violence and an understand
[normal]ing of the needs of the other. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We know that these encounters work by the interesting and often very poignant feedback forms students fill in at the end of the meeting.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We manage to reach an average of 15,000 students each year.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We have a follow up meeting
[normal] with the students which includes the screening of “Two Sided Story”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]a documentary produced by the Parents Circle – Families Forum, which illustrates the narrative of both sides.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This documentary is based on an adult workshop run by the PCFF.
[normal]4b.
[normal] 
[normal]Summer Ca
[normal]mp – Youth Programme
[normal]It is the children caught in the midst of the Israeli
[normal]-
[normal]Palestinian conflict who have paid the highest price of all:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]they have suffered the trauma of losing an immediate family member.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Each year the
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] PCFF
[normal] r
[normal]uns a 
[normal]s
[normal]ummer 
[normal]c
[normal]amp for bereaved children and their friends. The children are aged 14 to 18.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Some of the facilitators today have been to the 
[normal]s
[normal]ummer 
[normal]c
[normal]amp themselves and so there is an ongoing commitment to peace after they participate.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Today with Face
[normal]b
[normal]ook the participants 
[normal]are able to keep in touch during the year and
[normal],
[normal] dependent on budget
[normal],
[normal] we arrange meetings. The programme includes social games, dialogue, workshops, physical activities, Arabic and Hebrew language lessons and joint creative projects and expressions of their 
[normal]learning.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]These activities aim at building trust among the youth.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Some activities are competitive, where mixed bi-national groups experience work
[normal]ing
[normal] together as teams
[normal]. 
[normal]Palestinian and Israeli youth alike come away from their experience in the 
[normal]y
[normal]outh program
[normal] with increased knowledge of the other, with a sense of connection to one another that was built regardless of religious, cultural, national or ethnic ties.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The sense of shared humanity that existed for many before
[normal],
[normal] was cemented by this experience.
