[normal]4d.
[normal] 
[normal]Social
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Media
[normal]The past several years of the Israeli-Palestinian conflict have been characterized by an absence and stalling of any political or diplomatic dialogue.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Both sides vie
[normal]w the other with distrust and skepticism and not as partners for making peace.
[normal]Today,
[normal] on the
[normal] front line in the public opinion battle are social media platforms like Facebook
[normal], which is
[normal] very influential among Israelis and Palestinians
[normal]. A 
[normal]third of 
[normal]all 
[normal]Palesti
[normal]nians and around 
[normal]45
[normal] percent of Israelis are active on Facebook
[normal],
[normal] but even on Facebook Israelis and Palestinians are mostly exposed to their own communities and to voices of criticism and hatred 
[normal]on
[normal] 
[normal]both sides.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]They do
[normal] 
[normal]n
[normal]o
[normal]t hear enough 
[normal]alternative
[normal] voices and especially the unique voice of the PCFF
[normal].
[normal]The PCFF launched the Crack in the Wall (CITW)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](
[normal]http://www.facebook.com/crackinthewall
[normal])
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] in order to foster interaction between Palestinians and Is
[normal]raelis and to facilitate more opportunities for changing attitudes, breaking down stereotypes and humanizing the conflicted societies in order to break the cycle of violence.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] The uniqueness of this network is that all its entries are published in Hebrew a
[normal]nd Arabic
[normal],
[normal] allowing users to express themselves in their own language.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Research has shown that technologies of communication like social media platforms have an enabling effect.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]They have acted as a catalyst to facilitate and accelerate social change alrea
[normal]dy happening on the ground. Since the Crack in the Wall was launched in April 2012 it has provided a platform for more than 20,000 people, the majority of them Israelis and Palestinians.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It has brought to the forefront the fact that there are Israelis and 
[normal]Palestinians who want to be engaged and who are determined to work together to 
[normal]change the
[normal] status quo. In 2013 the Crack in the Wall project won the prestigious 
[normal]United Nations Alliance of Civilizations (UNAOC)
[normal]/BMW
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]award.
[normal]We are 
[normal]also 
[normal]proud of our website 
[normal]www.theparentscircle.com
[normal] which publicises our activities 
[normal]in English, Hebrew and Arabic.
